@page
@model HowItWorksModel
@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "How this works";
}

<h1>@ViewData["Title"]</h1>

<p class="lead">
    This is a standard ASP.NET Core Razor Pages app running on Vercel as a container.
</p>

<p>
    There's no special adapter or serverless shim involved &mdash; it's the stock
    <code>dotnet new webapp</code> template. Deployment works because the repo ships a
    <code>Dockerfile.vercel</code> at its root:
</p>

<ul>
    <li>
        Vercel detects <code>Dockerfile.vercel</code> and routes all traffic to the resulting
        image, which it builds, pushes, and deploys on every commit.
    </li>
    <li>
        The image runs as an OCI container on <strong>Fluid compute</strong> &mdash; not a
        traditional always-on server &mdash; so it autoscales and scales to zero when idle,
        billing only for active CPU.
    </li>
    <li>
        The only real contract is <strong>HTTP on a port</strong>: Vercel injects a
        <code>PORT</code> environment variable, and <code>Program.cs</code> binds
        <code>http://0.0.0.0:$PORT</code>. TLS is terminated at the edge, so the container
        just speaks plain HTTP.
    </li>
    <li>
        A multi-stage build compiles with the .NET SDK image, then ships on the minimal
        <code>aspnet:10.0-noble-chiseled</code> runtime (no shell or package manager, runs
        as a non-root user).
    </li>
</ul>

<p>
    Learn more in the Vercel docs:
    <a href="https://vercel.com/kb/guide/does-vercel-support-docker-deployments" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        Does Vercel support Docker deployments?
    </a>
    and the announcement,
    <a href="https://vercel.com/blog/dockerfile-on-vercel" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        Run any Dockerfile on Vercel
    </a>.
</p>
